1. Abstract

Atlantic tropical cyclones inflict massive economic and human losses, but their slow progress across the ocean offers a rare opportunity for early preparation. This study investigates whether a cyclones formation-day weather conditions can predict its ultimate destructive potential, proxied using accumulated cyclone energy (ACE) and other intrinsic storm metrics like central pressure, storm size, and forward speed. We hypothesized that, while imperfect, the conditions of formation could reveal some level of explanatory power for the storm's eventual strength. If successful, this approach could provide a practical tool for emergency management personnel to extend the disaster-preparation horizon and support proactive resource allocation, much earlier than the 5-day horizon limiting today's sophisticated physical simulations.

Using primarily government data, we compiled data for 1,991 cyclones from 1851-2024, combining best-track observations with high-resolution reanalysis datasets for air temperature, vertical wind shear, sea surface temperature, relative humidity, African Easterly Wave strength, convective available potential energy, and regional climate indices. For each of our four outcome variables of interest, we train models with eight different regression methods (including nonlinear and nonparametric options), optimized using 5-fold cross-validation within a reusable modeling pipeline.

Results indicate that the formation-day conditions we studied carry zero predictive signal, preventing early assessment of the damage potential for newborn cyclones, with our best results being only slightly better than random guessing. While we still believe in the resource allocation value of earlier cyclone strength prediction, we do not recommend further study of doing so using only the weather conditions at the storm's formation.

2. Project background

Major tropical cyclones in the Atlantic basin cause billions of USD in damage and can kill thousands. As of February 2025, the aggregate cost of damages from weather and climate disasters in the US is $2.915 trillion. U.S. government statistics (e.g., NOAA, FEMA) report an average of approximately 24 immediate deaths per tropical cyclone nationally. Young & Hsiang (2023) shows that each tropical cyclone actually causes 7,00011,000 total deaths, when long-term delayed or indirect deaths are included (e.g. disrupted health care, environmental exposure). Seasonal tropical cyclone activity is increasing as global temperatures rise, with warmer oceans fueling more frequent and more intense major storms.

Tropical cyclones notably can take several days to make landfall, when they cause their damage. Unlike many other natural disasters (e.g. earthquakes, wildfires, floods, landslides, avalanches, volcanoes), these often provide significant advance notice and thus the unique opportunity for preparations that can save lives and limit damage. Accurate early prediction of a cyclones path and strength allows emergency management personnel to develop evacuation plans and defensive measures and to stage resources and financing.

Today, cyclone models are immensely sophisticated dynamic physical simulations using first principles. The complexity allows meteorological predictions to be highly accurate, but at the same time it greatly hampers how much earlier confident predictions can be made. NOAAs National Hurricane Center issues 5-day intensity forecasts, but cyclones from the Main Development Region (MDR) off the coast of West Africa can take up to two weeks to make landfall. Beyond five days, the dynamic simulations are too uncertain.

Hurricanes cause damage through countless of climate variables, where when they interact, the direct wind field can destroy roofs, windows, and infrastrucures on the land, that it is known as the constliest natural disasters in the United States (Ghahremani, et al., 2024). Some of the destructive force come from the storm's instrisic and extrinsic cahcaterstics, such as wind speed, central pressure size, precipitation intensity, and forward speed for instrinsic components. The hurricanes are able to damage on-land properties and risking people's lives by the mix of conditions, such as wind speed & pressure, storm path/size, and coastal/ocean geometry that jointly influence storm surge. This relates strongly to the surge-driven damage (Islam, et al., 2021). Meanwhile, extrinsic factors highly depend on the environment the storm occurs, where the amplification of the features, such as steepness of the continental shelf and the angle at which the storm approaches the coast, will cause damage to the location where the hurricane hits (Pandey & Rao, 2019). This also relates to flooding, which can be driven both by the amount of rainfall a storm produces and by pre-existing environmental conditions. For example, if the ground is already saturated from recent rain, additional precipitation can easily lead to severe flooding. These outcomes depend on a combination of intrinsic storm factors and extrinsic environmental parameters.

3. Project objective

Our objective is to explore how well an Atlantic cyclones ultimate damage potential can be predicted with statistical learning only from its conditions of formation. If successful, approximately correct predictions can inform early stages of a government response plan.

Our efforts may easily fail. There is a reason meteorologists use the physical simulations to model cyclone development: Atlantic cyclones evolve dramatically over their life as they travel westward through different atmospheric and oceanic conditions. Their trajectory is so dependent on conditions away from their origin that we consider it a non-starter to attempt to predict landfall location.

The project hypothesis is that statistical learning can allow officials to anticipate the approximate destructive power of a cyclone from the day it forms, which can be up to two weeks before it arrives, and up to 10 days earlier than a physical simulation could.

4. Input data description

4.1 Outcomes & prediction problems

As the primary proxy metric for damage potential, we predict the cyclones accumulated cyclone energy: a unitless index calculated as the sum of squares of six-hour observations for its maximum sustained wind speed over its life at tropical storm strength. We choose this value because it is intrinsic to the storm rather than being a function of its landfall location and timing and arose from scientific efforts to characterize a cyclones destruction potential.

We have acquired this data for 1,991 cyclones dating from 1851 through 2024 Atlantic hurricane seasons.

As secondary prediction problems, we also seek to predict additional intrinsic factors associated with cyclone damage, where there was available labeling data:

  • minimum central pressure, in mb 1,991 cyclones
  • mean forward speed, in km/hr 1,960 cyclones
  • maximum storm size, in km$^2$ 349 cyclones

A storms intrinsic factors must be independent of where, when, or whether it makes landfall, so we use these aggregate measures as proxy for its destructive potential.

4.2 Predictors

For predictors, we consider the conditions of the cyclones formation, where applicable at particular pressure levels (i.e. altitudes) associated with driving cyclogenesis:

  • location (latitude and longitude)
  • year
  • day of year, as a measure of seasonality
  • air temperature (250 & 500 mb), in K
  • monthly North Atlantic Oscillation index (CRU Gibraltar-Stykkisholmur)
  • monthly Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation index (UK Met Office HadSST 4)

Studies show cyclogenesis is related to weather conditions in the preceding days and weeks, so we are also including some predictor values for 0, 3, 7, and 14 days before formation (Richardson et al., 2025):

  • vertical wind shear between 200 & 850 mb, in m/s
  • sea surface temperature, in K
  • mid-level relative humidity (600 mb), in %

Lastly, certain predictors are associated with cyclone formation on a shorter time frame, so we include the following with lead times of 0, 2, and 3 days:

  • African Easterly Wave (AEW) strength, in s$^{-1}$
  • convective available potential energy (CAPE), in J/kg

4.3 Datasets

Our data collection approach is to identify the formation date and location for all recorded Atlantic cyclones and use those space-time coordinates to associate the formation conditions with each cyclone.

The raw hurricane and climate datasets required careful preprocessing to create a consistent framework.

The anchor of our data is the U.S. National Hurricane Centers revised Atlantic hurricane database (HURDAT2). The first observation for each storm (identified by a unique code) is used as the formation date and coordinates.

We compile dozens of gridded climate datasets for different metrics, pressure levels, and time periods in order to match the weather conditions at the time and place the cyclone first formed.

For each gridded dataset (ERA5, NCEP Reanalysis II, OISST, AEW tracks), we define a bounded subregion in the Atlantic Ocean covering the formation coordinates of all cyclones in the historical record. This reduced the volume of data downloaded and focused only on the spatial domain relevant to cyclogenesis.

For many of the datasets, we extract gridded NetCDF4 files for the bounded subregion in the Atlantic Ocean within which all cyclones formed. These are higher-dimensional tables, with the scalar values registered by latitude, longitude, pressure level, and time, so they cannot be excerpted here. Because we are interested in specific pressure levels associated with cyclogenesis, and each year of records is available separately, we made use of the data stores export tools to pull only those relevant records. Even so, this amounts to dozens of gigabytes of gridded data.

It is infeasible to upload such a high volume of data to a cloud environment or to process it there. Instead, for each indicator of interest, we use an individual Jupyter Notebook in a local environment to match the formation coordinates to the nearest recorded value in the data (and in some cases, calculate a derived statistic) and export a lightweight CSV for later merging and analysis. For predictors where we are interested in conditions in the days leading up to formation, this approach streamlines the lookup procedure.

See the bottom of this notebook for a link to a public GitHub repository containing our pre-processed data files and the notebooks used to create them.

5. Data cleaning

5.1 Cleaning

Due to the nature of our gridded climate data sources, most of our cleaning work is done in the individual Jupyter Notebooks where we process each metric.

In most cases, missing data is not randomly distributed but rather a function of the temporal range of the dataset, so we handle this by truncating our temporal scope where needed. When this is not the case, we impute values with interpolation. Fortunately, this only occurred in tabular sources, as we could not have properly interpolated the gridded data. For instance, in the Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation, we used a spline interpolation to best match the oscillating value.

Since most of our data sources are re-analyses and the result of interpolating historical data to begin with, there were no instances of outliers.

We also verified data types and time zones to ensure proper matching with the base HURDAT2 database.

5.2 Merging

Here, we import the packages we require, define a fixed random seed to make our results repeatable, and compile our overall design matrix by merging on our primary key: each cyclone's unique ID code. We then examine the resulting DataFrame and tabulate the non-null data to ensure the merge completed as expected:

5.3 Overview of missing patterns

The hurricane dataset spans 18512024, but not all predictors exist across this entire period. The availability of each variable depends on when the underlying observational or reanalysis dataset began.

We observe two main groups of predictors:

  1. Predictors with maximum historical coverage (18512024): These variables are available for nearly all storms, with very few missing cells: relative humidity (rhum_minus_*), sea surface temperature (sst_minus_*), vertical wind shear (vws_minus_*), climate indices (amo, nao), upper-air temperature (air_temp_250mb, air_temp_500mb).

    • Reason: These variables are available in 20th-Century re-analyses or from long-standing historical records.
    • Result: These predictors can be used for models covering the entire historical hurricane record.

  2. Predictors beginning in the "Satellite Era" (1979 onward): Some predictors show large blocks of missing values prior to 1979: African Easterly Wave strength (aew_strength_minus_*), convective available potential energy (cape_minus_*).

    • Reason: These are derived from ERA5 and other satellite-era reanalysis datasets, which only begin around 1979. Hurricanes prior to that date simply do not have these measurements, so missing values are structural.
    • Result: Models that include AEW/CAPE predictors must be limited to 19792023.

Due to this, we will use two dataframes with two different periods (1851-2024) and (1979-2023).

#2.3 Make function
def plot_all_predictors_vs_target(data, predictor_groups, target_col, target_label, cols=3):

    #Flatten data
    all_vars = []
    for group in predictor_groups.values():
        all_vars.extend(group)

    n = len(all_vars)
    rows = math.ceil(n / cols)

    #Figure and axes
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(
        rows, cols,
        figsize=(cols * 4.5, rows * 3.6),
        squeeze=False
    )
    axes = axes.flatten()

    #Colorbar space
    fig.subplots_adjust(
        left=0.08,
        right=0.86,
        top=0.90,
        bottom=0.08,
        hspace=0.35,  #Vertical spacing between rows
        wspace=0.25   #Horizontal spacing between columns
    )

    #Shared colorbar
    years = data["year"].dropna()
    norm = plt.Normalize(vmin=years.min(), vmax=years.max())
    cmap = "inferno"

    first_scatter = None

    #Plotting data
    for i, (col, label, unit) in enumerate(all_vars):
        ax = axes[i]
        sub = data.dropna(subset=[col, target_col, "year"])

        sc = ax.scatter(
            sub[col], sub[target_col],
            c=sub["year"],
            cmap=cmap,
            norm=norm,
            s=12,
            alpha=0.7
        )

        if first_scatter is None:
            first_scatter = sc

        ax.set_title(label, fontsize=10)
        ax.set_xlabel(label if unit == "" else f"{label} ({unit})", fontsize=8)
        ax.set_ylabel(target_label, fontsize=8)
        ax.grid(True, alpha=0.2)

    #Remove unused axes (if any)
    for j in range(n, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    #Bar
    cbar = fig.colorbar(
        first_scatter,
        ax=axes,
        orientation="vertical",
        fraction=0.04,   #Width of colorbar
        pad=0.02         #Distance from plots
    )
    cbar.set_label("Year", fontsize=10)
    cbar.ax.tick_params(labelsize=8)

    #Main title
    fig.suptitle(f"{target_label} vs Predictors", fontsize=16, fontweight="bold")

    plt.show()

The data describes many standard outcome distributions, and the summary statistics reflect the same patterns, showing that most outcomes are highly skewed. The dataset includes 1,983 storms, merged with several additional datasets whose time ranges and data granularities differ. The outcome variables tend to be skewed with extreme storms driving much of the variation. This is reflected in their large standard deviations, such as peak size (std 1.8610 km).

Meanwhile, the environmental predictors shows broad natural variability but generally have more moderate standard deviations, such as SST (std 1.59 K), relative humidity (std 17%), and mid- and upper-level temperatures. These SD values indicate that predictors vary across storms and lead times. Generally, the dataset provides both high-variance outcomes and diverse predictor ranges.

7. Forecasting and prediction modeling

We aimed to predict a cyclones destructive potential using only formation-day conditions, using ACE, minimum central pressure, maximum storm size, and mean forward speed as our outcomes.

For each problem, we prepared the dataset by removing rows with missing predictor values and generating design matrices containing all relevant formation-day variables. Features were scaled within the modeling pipeline, using standardization for roughly normal distributions and min-max scaling for highly skewed features.

We tested eight regression approaches, representing both linear and nonlinear learning methods:

  • Forward stepwise selection

  • Backward stepwise selection

  • LASSO regression

  • Ridge regression

  • k-Nearest Neighbors

  • Simple decision tree

  • Random forest

  • Gradient boosting

For each method, we performed 5-fold cross-validation to select optimal hyperparameters (e.g. number of neighbors, regularization strengths, tree depth, number of estimators).

7.3 Training

Here, we compare eight regression methods:

  • Forward stepwise selection
  • Backward stepwise selection
  • LASSO regression
  • Ridge regression
  • k-Nearest Neighbors
  • Simple decision tree
  • Random forest
  • Gradient boosting

In order to streamline our training procedure, we define each problem as a set of attributes (time bounds, outcome, and predictors) that we can feed into reusable functions.

We define five problems in a configuration object. Four represent the four outcome variables of interest: ACE, minimum central pressure, maximum storm size, and mean forward speed. Depending on the time range for these outcome labels, we use start and end years to truncate the rows and choose predictors where we have 95% coverage, dropping the last few rows containing any null values.

The fifth problem again considers our primary prediction question: ACE. This time, we restrict our time frame to the "satellite era" of meteorology, beginning in 1979, so that we can make use of relevant predictors like CAPE and AEW strength.

We now define several functions:

  • One for each method of regression analysis cross-validation and final training
  • A function for evaluating the performance of a model
  • A "pipeline" function that accepts a problem definition, generates the design matrix appropriately, splits and scales the data, trains and evaluates the model, and appends the results to a dictionary.

We scale each feature with standardization if it is roughly bell-shaped, and with min-max if not. We must conduct scaling after the split to avoid data leakage.

For each method, we performed 5-fold cross-validation to select optimal hyperparameters (number of neighbors, regularization strengths, tree depth, number of estimators).

In[26]:
def evaluate(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
	y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)
	y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)
	train_mse = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
	test_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
	train_rmse = np.sqrt(train_mse)
	test_rmse = np.sqrt(test_mse)
	train_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
	test_mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)
	train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
	test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
	return [train_mse, test_mse, train_rmse, test_rmse, train_mae, test_mae, train_r2, test_r2]

def run_forward_selection(X_train, y_train):
	lrf = LinearRegression()
	sfs = SequentialFeatureSelector(lrf, direction='forward', cv=KFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True,random_state=seed))

	pipe_lrf = Pipeline([
		('sfs', sfs),
		('model', lrf)
	])

	param_grid = {
		'sfs__n_features_to_select': range(1, X_train.shape[1])
	}

	grid_search_forward = GridSearchCV(pipe_lrf, param_grid, cv=KFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True,random_state=seed), scoring='r2')
	grid_search_forward.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return grid_search_forward.best_estimator_
In[28]:
def run_backward_selection(X_train, y_train):
	lrb = LinearRegression()
	sfs = SequentialFeatureSelector(lrb, direction='backward', cv=KFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True,random_state=seed))

	pipe_lrb = Pipeline([
		('sfs', sfs),
		('model', lrb)
	])

	param_grid = {
		'sfs__n_features_to_select': range(1, X_train.shape[1])
	}

	grid_search_backward = GridSearchCV(pipe_lrb, param_grid, cv=KFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True,random_state=seed), scoring='r2')
	grid_search_backward.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return grid_search_backward.best_estimator_
In[29]:
def run_lasso(X_train, y_train):
	lasso_cv = LassoCV(cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed), alphas=100, random_state=seed, max_iter=5000)
	lasso_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return lasso_cv

def run_ridge(X_train, y_train):
	ridge_cv = RidgeCV(cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed), alphas=np.logspace(-3,3,50), scoring='r2')
	ridge_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return ridge_cv

def run_knn_regressor(X_train, y_train):
	pipe_knn = Pipeline([
		('knn', KNeighborsRegressor())

		'knn__n_neighbors': range(1, 30)
	}

	return grid_search_knn.best_estimator_

def run_decision_tree(X_train, y_train):
	dtr = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=seed)

		'min_samples_leaf': [1, 3, 5, 10],
		'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10]
	}

In[33]:
def run_random_forest(X_train, y_train):
	rfr = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=seed)

	param_dist = {
		'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
		'max_features': ['sqrt'],
		'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 7],
		'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
		'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10]
	}

	random_search_rf = RandomizedSearchCV(
		rfr,
		param_distributions=param_dist,
		n_iter=25,
		cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=seed),
		scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
		random_state=seed,
		refit=True
	)

	random_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return random_search_rf.best_estimator_

def run_gradient_boosting(X_train, y_train):
	gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=seed)

	param_dist = {
		'n_estimators': [100, 200, 500],
		'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2],
		'max_depth': [3, 4, 5, 7],
		'subsample': [0.8, 0.9, 1.0]
	}

	random_search_gb = RandomizedSearchCV(
		gbr,
		param_distributions=param_dist,
		n_iter=25,
		cv=KFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True,random_state=seed),
		scoring="neg_mean_squared_error",
		random_state=seed
	)

	random_search_gb.fit(X_train, y_train)
	return random_search_gb.best_estimator_

def run_pipeline(id, config):
	data = df.copy()

	# drop
	mask = data.year.between(config['start_year'], config['end_year'])
	data = data[mask]
	data.dropna(inplace=True)

	# split
	X = data[config['predictors']].copy()
	y = data[config['outcome']].copy()

	X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = seed)

	# scale
	if config['start_year'] >= 1979:
		minmax_cols = [
			'aew_strength_minus_0_days', 'aew_strength_minus_2_days', 'aew_strength_minus_3_days',
			'cape_minus_0_days', 'cape_minus_2_days', 'cape_minus_3_days',
			'year'
		]
	else:
		minmax_cols = ['year']
	standard_cols = [
		'formation_lat', 'formation_lon', 'day_of_year',
		'air_temp_250mb', 'amo', 'nao',
		'rhum_minus_0_days', 'rhum_minus_3_days', 'rhum_minus_7_days', 'rhum_minus_14_days',
		'sst_minus_0_days',
		'vws_minus_0_days', 'vws_minus_3_days', 'vws_minus_7_days', 'vws_minus_14_days'
	]

	preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
		transformers = [
			('minmax', MinMaxScaler(), minmax_cols),
			('standard', StandardScaler(), standard_cols),
		],
		remainder = 'passthrough'
	)

	X_train = preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)
	X_test = preprocessor.transform(X_test)
	X_train.columns = minmax_cols + standard_cols # Rename to get rid of the scaler prefixes that got added
	X_test.columns = minmax_cols + standard_cols

	# model
	scores = pd.DataFrame(columns=['train_mse','test_mse', 'train_rmse','test_rmse','train_mae', 'test_mae', 'train_r2', 'test_r2'])
	best_models = {}

	methods = ["Forward selection", "Backward selection", "Lasso", "Ridge", "KNN", "Decision tree", "Random forest", "Gradient boosting"]
	routines = [run_forward_selection, run_backward_selection, run_lasso, run_ridge, run_knn_regressor, run_decision_tree, run_random_forest, run_gradient_boosting]

	for j, routine in enumerate(routines):
		model = routine(X_train, y_train)
		scores.loc[methods[j]] = evaluate(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)
		best_models[methods[j]] = model

	results[id] = {
		"scores": scores,
		"best_models": best_models,
		"X_train": X_train,
		"y_train": y_train,
		"X_test": X_test,
		"y_test": y_test
	}

Here, we run our routines on all problem definitions. The result is a dictionary object containing the 8 best models for each regression method and a table of loss statistics, for each problem.

7.4 Visualization & reactions

We immediately see from the results that our $R^2$ scores are abysmal across the board. All models for all problems are, at best, slightly better than random guessing, and often even worse than that.

Our overall best performer is a gradient boosting regressor for mean forward speed, with $R^2 = 14.3\%$.

Now, we use visualization to dig deeper into the poor performance. First, we examine residual plots for the training error:

8. Resource allocation and conclusions

8.1 Resource allocation

Although our damage proxies (ACE, minimum pressure, storm size, forward speed) are indirect substitutes for real economic loss, they represent intrinsic cyclone intensity and therefore provide a meaningful way to test early-stage predictability.

Unfortunately, our models failed at accomplishing this. However, the resource allocation question is still of interest: How can emergency management decision-makers best anticipate future resource deployment needs from an incoming cyclone?

Most hurricane damage is from a combination of high wind speed and storm surge, which is itself a function of wind speed and pressure, along with extrinsic characteristics of the location of landfall. The larger a cyclone is, the more widespread its damage. The slower it moves, the longer it pummels the towns it hits.

Because our models use only formation-day conditions, if they worked, they could have extended the planning window by up to 1014 days depending on the formation spot, which is well before physical intensity forecasts become reliable. Even approximate forecasts help agencies triage storms and decide where to focus limited resources.

ACE predictions could have allowed agencies to quickly flag storms with high destructive potential, enabling pre-emptive mobilization of evacuation transport, hospital surge capacity, emergency fuel reserves and coastal protection teams before the storm begins intensifying. Officials can ramp up resource deployment over a longer time period. Early knowledge of a cyclones destructive potential also helps state governments determine whether to request federal assistance sooner, and how much. Moreover, being able to forecast central pressure, storm size, and forward speed supports more informed resource planning.

Our secondary prediction problems also would have been useful information to these decision makers: Low central pressure, large storm size, and low forward speed can cause significantly more damage to life and property through sustained wind and storm surge than another cyclone with the same top wind speed.

Quantitatively, it is difficult to characterize our particular resource allocation question. We deliberately avoid dollar amounts of damage as a metric because, as noted above, it is so dependent on extrinsic properties like location of landfall, angle of approach, steepness of ocean shelf, and pre-existing ground saturation from previous rainfall. However, an analysis by NOAA's National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI) on the inflation-adjusted cost of U.S. cyclones highlights how the most costly cyclones were not the highest wind speeds. For example, Hurricane Katrina (ranked first, $210.3B) was Category 3, and Hurricane Sandy (ranked fifth, $88.5B) was only a Category 1. This emphasizes the importance of our secondary outcome variables in painting a more comprehensive picture of a cyclone's intrinsic destructive potential. We acknowledge that, without precise foresight of the landfall, any resource allocation application of a successful version of our model would necessarily have to be fairly broad in terms of dollar amounts.

So, while we are convinced of the importance of our research questions, we are disappointed in the failure of the models.

8.2 Conclusions

As illustrated above, our regression models for various indicators of ultimate cyclone destructive power uniformly failed to make accurate predictions based solely on weather conditions at time of formation.

We acknowledged this would potentially be the result of our study from the outset, given the incredible sophistication of the physical simulations used by meteorologists today. Our fears were strengthened by the lack of visible relationships between our many predicts and any of our four outcome variables, and then finally confirmed by our results. The weak associations across predictors indicate that the environmental factors present on, or immediately before, the formation day explain only a very small portion of the variability in the conditions that fuel a cyclones eventual strength.

We believe we executed well on the principles of data analysis and showcased good habits in our data collection, cleaning, and training steps, but ultimately it is clear that, at minimum, the predictors we selected are far from sufficient on their own to explain a cyclone's eventual power to any degree.

Because there are only so many cyclones in recorded history, we sought to include data as far back as we could. In order to check whether this was a mistake, we ran an alternate problem only on more recent, satellite-gathered data as well. In the end, neither time period of our predictors showed any explanatory power.

It is possible that a more comprehensive model could outperform ours, but our results are so convincing in their lack of applicability, that we do not recommend further study on this front.
